---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Enoch C., MSc — Research & Editorial | MoodSupplement"
  description="Enoch C. is the research and editorial lead at MoodSupplement. MSc Business Administration (Health), University of Groningen, 2025. Evidence-based supplement reviews."
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 pt-12 pb-16">

    <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-start sm:items-center gap-6 mb-8">
      <img
        src="/images/authors/enoch-c.png"
        alt="Enoch C."
        width="80"
        height="80"
        class="rounded-full w-20 h-20 object-cover object-top shrink-0 border-2 border-mist"
      />
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow mb-1">Research & Editorial</p>
        <h1 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-moss-deep">Enoch C., MSc</h1>
        <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1 text-sm">MoodSupplement — Founder & Research Lead</p>
        <p class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-soft mt-0.5">
          MSc Business Administration (Health) · University of Groningen · 2025
        </p>
        <a
          href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/enoch-cheung-ec/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 mt-2 font-mono text-xs text-moss-deep hover:text-saffron-deep underline-offset-2 hover:underline"
        >
          LinkedIn profile →
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-mr">
      <p>
        Enoch C. holds an MSc in Business Administration (Health) from the University of Groningen
        with graduate training in health economics, healthcare systems, and
        evidence-based decision-making. He founded MoodSupplement to apply that analytical lens to
        the supplement market — reading primary research, assigning evidence tiers, and stating the
        caveats as clearly as the claims.
      </p>

      <h2>How I review supplements</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Primary research, not aggregators.</strong> Each supplement profile draws on the
          actual trials and meta-analyses — RCTs, systematic reviews, Cochrane assessments — not
          manufacturer summaries or secondary health sites.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Honest evidence tiers.</strong> Every supplement is rated Emerging, Moderate, or
          Well-studied based on the weight and consistency of human trials. One favourable study
          means Emerging; that rating doesn't shift because a product is popular.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Cautions stated plainly.</strong> Interaction risks and safety notes appear at
          the top of the page, not buried below the buy button. The 5-HTP serotonin-syndrome
          warning is the clearest example — it leads the page because it has to.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Support framing, never treatment claims.</strong> Supplements are described as
          mood, stress and sleep <em>support</em>. Nothing on this site claims to treat, diagnose,
          or cure any condition. Professional care always comes first.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        For the full editorial methodology — how quality criteria are sourced, how products are
        verified, and how conflicts of interest are managed — see the{' '}
        <a href="/about/">About & editorial standards</a> page.
      </p>

      <h2>See the work</h2>
      <p>
        <a href="/products/">Browse all supplement reviews</a> — ten evidence-rated profiles covering
        mood, stress and sleep support.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/blog/">Browse the research guides</a> — in-depth articles on the science behind
        specific supplements and how they interact with the body.
      </p>
    </div>

  </section>
</Base>
